For your specific needs—quick dismissal, a persistent history list, and easy scripting—there are three main players.

1. SwayNotificationCenter (SwayNC) - The "Control Center" Choice
This is currently the gold standard for Hyprland users who want a "Notification Center" experience similar to macOS or GNOME.

Why it fits: It has a built-in "Control Center" (a side panel) that holds all your old notifications. You can clear them all at once or individually.

Waybar Integration: It integrates perfectly. You can add a dedicated icon to Waybar that shows the number of unread notifications and opens the panel when clicked.

Dismissal: Supports mouse clicks and keyboard shortcuts to dismiss popups instantly.

Command: swaync-client -t (to toggle the panel).

2. Mako - The Lightweight Specialist
Mako is the classic Wayland-native choice. It’s much lighter than SwayNC but doesn't have a built-in "history panel" UI by default.

Why it fits: It’s incredibly fast and follows the "do one thing well" philosophy.

History: You have to use makoctl restore to bring back the last notification, or script a dmenu/rofi frontend to view a "list." It’s more for minimalists who rarely check history.

Dismissal: Very fast; makoctl dismiss or just click.

3. Dunst - The Old Reliable
Dunst is the "OG" and works on Wayland now too. It’s extremely customizable via a flat config file.

Why it fits: Like Mako, it's very lightweight.

History: Uses dunstctl history-pop to see old stuff.

Cons: It's an X11 tool at its core. While it works on Wayland, it doesn't always handle HiDPI or multi-monitor setups as elegantly as Mako or SwayNC.

How to script it (The "Notification-Shite" Part)
Regardless of which daemon you pick, they all follow the Desktop Bus (DBus) specification. You don't need a specific tool for each daemon; you just use notify-send (part of the libnotify package).

Install the basics:

Bash
sudo pacman -S libnotify sway-notification-center  # Or mako / dunst
Send a notification from any script:

Bash
# Basic popup
notify-send "System Update" "Your kernel has been updated."

# With an icon and urgency (stays on screen longer/different color)
notify-send -u critical -i software-update-available "Panic!" "Something went wrong."

# Custom "shite" script:
# Save this as ~/bin/notif
#!/bin/bash
notify-send "$1" "${2:-Default body text}"
Recommendation
If you want that "list of old notifications" without writing your own UI, SwayNotificationCenter is the winner.

Install: yay -S swaynotificationcenter

Auto-start: Add exec-once = swaync to your hyprland.conf.

Waybar: Add the custom/notification module to your Waybar config to see the history count.

